sp.p:
What ſay you to Plato, who reports,Plato. that Socrates being in priſon, foretold vnto Crito his owne death, which ſhould be three dayes after, becauſe a faire young woman had appearred to him in his dreame, who called him by his name, repeating vnto him that verſe of the Greeke Poet;
Tertia te Pithei tempeſtas laeta locabit.
which punctually fell out.

We cannot but blame the expoſition of dreames;
                              Eccle. 34. 
                           Eccleſiaſticus, ſaying: Dreames extoll fooles, as he which apprehends ſhaddow, and followes the wind: ſo very a foole is he who obſerues dreames, as hee which troubles himſelfe in vaine to embrace a ſhaddow, and to follow the winde.
